    <Descriptive_Notes>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Quasi-ceremonial, tapestry-woven pictorial rugs featuring representations of the yei, the Navajo Holy People, as they were depicted in sand paintings.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>English</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000000/VP</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000024211/Kaufman and Selser, Navajo Weaving Tradition (1985)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Alfombras pictóricas de tapicería tejidas cuasi ceremoniales, que exhiben representaciones del yei, el pueblo sagrado navajo, como ellos fueron representados en pinturas de arena.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Spanish</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000131/CDBP-SNPC</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000051034/TAA database (2000-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Quasi-ceremoniële, handgemaakte tapijten met afbeeldingen van de yei, het heilige Navajo-volk, zoals die in zandschilderingen werden afgebeeld.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Dutch</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
